GBT regression of separated drop-cast/spin-coat subset further demonstrates the generic character of stability reversal in perovskites: higher ratio of MA to Cs, MA to Rb, or FA to Cs normally produces better stability below 100 °C while it produces worse stability above 100 °C (Supplementary Fig. 7). Meanwhile, by comparing the T80 of Cs/MA-containing samples, we find that 140 °C-T80 shows an increasing trend from No. 22 (Cs0.05FA0.95PbI3) to No. 26 (Cs0.30FA0.70PbI3), while this trend is almost reversed for 85 °C-T80 (Fig. 2a). No. 53 → 55, No. 57 → 59, No. 61 → 63, and No. 8 → 11 show similar reversal behaviors. The Arrhenius plot further shows that kdec = 0.2/T80 of MA-rich perovskites grows faster than that of MA-poor perovskites (MA concentration <5%) as the ageing temperature rises, leading to a crossover at approximately 110 °C (Fig. 2e). This phenomenon is also observed in No. 28 vs. No. 22/23 with a crossover at ~85 °C (Supplementary Fig. 13). MAPbI3 (No. 32) also shows stability reversal with FAPbI3 (No. 1), indicated by the Arrhenius plot (Fig. 2f). An extrapolated crossover at ~15 °C is expected. The slope is correlated with the equivalent activation energy Eq. (2):2kdec=k0×e−EakBT\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
